1
00:00:00,080 --> 00:00:06,680
In this video we are going to learn cache aside pattern in distributed caching for microservices.

2
00:00:07,580 --> 00:00:13,460
A cache aside pattern is the most common caching strategy used in microservices.

3
00:00:13,490 --> 00:00:15,470
You can see the picture on the slide.

4
00:00:15,470 --> 00:00:16,970
We have three steps.

5
00:00:16,970 --> 00:00:20,000
Now I am going to explain these following steps.

6
00:00:20,930 --> 00:00:24,650
The first step is when a client needs to access data.

7
00:00:24,650 --> 00:00:28,460
It first checks to see if the data is in the cache.

8
00:00:29,030 --> 00:00:36,260
The second step is if the data is in the case, the client retrieves it from the cache and returns it

9
00:00:36,260 --> 00:00:37,550
to the caller system.

10
00:00:38,120 --> 00:00:45,230
And the third step is if the data is not in the cache, the client retrieves it from the database and

11
00:00:45,230 --> 00:00:49,490
stores it in the cache, and then returns it to the caller system.

12
00:00:50,370 --> 00:00:55,950
Some of the caching systems provide read through and write through or write behind operations.

13
00:00:55,950 --> 00:01:00,720
In these systems, client applications retrieves data over by the cache.

14
00:01:01,590 --> 00:01:08,040
For caches that don't provide this functionality, it is the responsibility of the applications that

15
00:01:08,040 --> 00:01:11,790
use the cache and update the cache if there is a cache miss.

16
00:01:12,060 --> 00:01:17,400
So a cache aside pattern comes to the picture and implements for these kind of cases.

17
00:01:17,400 --> 00:01:18,540
Microservices.

18
00:01:18,540 --> 00:01:21,870
Also a good example to implement cache aside pattern.

19
00:01:21,960 --> 00:01:28,350
In a microservice architecture, it is common to use a distributed cache that is shared across multiple

20
00:01:28,350 --> 00:01:29,160
services.

21
00:01:29,580 --> 00:01:35,880
This can be useful for storing data that is commonly accessed by the multiple services, or storing

22
00:01:35,880 --> 00:01:40,320
data that is expensive to compete or retrieve from a databases.

23
00:01:42,680 --> 00:01:48,620
Using the cache aside pattern can improve the performance of a microservice architecture by reducing

24
00:01:48,620 --> 00:01:52,460
the number of expensive database calls or data store lookups.

25
00:01:52,490 --> 00:01:59,390
It can also help to reduce the load on the database or data store, as many requests for data can be

26
00:01:59,390 --> 00:02:00,560
served from the cache.

27
00:02:01,580 --> 00:02:07,490
In order to use the cache aside pattern in microservices, you would need to implement a cache layer

28
00:02:07,490 --> 00:02:11,450
in your service that is responsible for managing the cache.

29
00:02:12,050 --> 00:02:18,710
This may involve using a cache library or framework such as Redis or Memcached, or implementing a custom

30
00:02:18,710 --> 00:02:19,640
cache solution.

31
00:02:21,380 --> 00:02:24,560
Here you can see the process of the cache aside pattern.

32
00:02:24,560 --> 00:02:30,530
When a service needs to access data, it first checks to see if the data is in the cache.

33
00:02:30,650 --> 00:02:36,530
If the data is in the cache, the service retrieves from the cache and returns it to the caller system.

34
00:02:36,590 --> 00:02:42,740
If the data is not in the cache, the service retrieves it from the database or other data store.

35
00:02:42,770 --> 00:02:48,500
And after that stores it into the cache, and after that then returns it to the caller system.

36
00:02:49,720 --> 00:02:54,280
So there are some drawbacks of using cache aside pattern for microservices.

37
00:02:54,310 --> 00:03:02,560
Cache can introduce additional complexity into our architecture or may not be suitable for all situations.

38
00:03:02,740 --> 00:03:10,030
For example, the cache may need to be invalidated or refreshed when the data is updated in the database,

39
00:03:10,030 --> 00:03:14,350
and this can require additional coordination between the microservices.

40
00:03:15,100 --> 00:03:22,450
And additionally the cache may introduce additional latency if it is located remotely from the microservices

41
00:03:22,450 --> 00:03:23,500
that are using it.

42
00:03:23,500 --> 00:03:28,630
So additional latency is also one of the drawbacks of using the distributed cache.

